Compensatory Control:
 
Technical Mitigation Controls (Host-Level Packet Filtering)
Strict firewalld Forwarding Policy: Implement an explicit forward zone policy in firewalld to block all forwarded traffic by default, except for explicitly defined sources and destinations.
Interface-Specific Restrictions: Bind the forwarding permissions strictly to the Podman bridge interface (e.g., podman0 or custom CNI bridge) and the primary physical interface (e.g., eth0). Run the following commands to isolate forwarded traffic:
 
# Ensure default forward policy is set to DROP
firewalld --permanent --direct --add-rule ipv4 filter FORWARD 0 -i eth0 -o podman0 -m state --state RELATED,ESTABLISHED -j ACCEPT
firewalld --permanent --direct --add-rule ipv4 filter FORWARD 0 -i podman0 -o eth0 -j ACCEPT
firewalld --permanent --direct --add-rule ipv4 filter FORWARD 1 -j DROP
firewalld –reload
 
Network Parameter Tightening: Disable reverse path filtering exceptions and source routing to prevent spoofing attacks on the routing engine by enforcing strict reverse path filtering in /etc/sysctl.d/99-security-hardening.conf:
net.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter = 1
net.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter = 1
net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0
net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0
net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects = 0 net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0
Procedural and Architectural Controls (Segmentation & Monitoring)
 
Network Micro-Segmentation: Place the registry server in a dedicated, isolated DeMilitarized Zone (DMZ) or restricted Tools VLAN. Configure upstream network firewalls (e.g., Palo Alto / Fortinet) with strict access control lists (ACLs) allowing ingress traffic to ports 443 or 5000 solely from authorized OpenShift cluster nodes.
 
Continuous Audit Logging & Monitoring: Enable Linux Audit Daemon (auditd) logging for any runtime modifications to network parameters and host routing tables. Add the following rules to /etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules:
-w /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward -p wa -k sysctl_network
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S sethostname -S setdomainname -k system-localization
 
SIEM Integration: Forward all host syslog and firewalld dropped-packet logs to the Centralized SIEM (e.g., Splunk / QRadar). Configure real-time alerts for any unauthorized connection attempts traversing the FORWARD chain.
